## GAN论文笔记

### 1. Abstract

- propose a new framework for estimating generative models via an adversarial process
- simultaneously train two models:  $G$ captures data distribution, and $D$ that estimates the where sample came.
- $G$ and $D$ are defined by multilayer perceptrons

### 2. Introduction

The promise of DL is to discover models that represent probability distributions.

The most striking successes is discrimntv model (mapping high-dim inputs to label)

Deep generative models have had less of an impact: 

- due to the difficulty of probabilistic computations that arise in MLE and related strategies
- due to difficulty of leveraging the benefits of piecewise linear units in the generative context. 

We propose a new generative model estimation procedure that sidesteps these difficulties.

In the proposed adversarial nets framework: 

- discriminator learns to determine whether a sample is from the model distribution or the data distribution. 
- generator trying to produce fake sample and use it

In this article, the generative model generates samples by passing random noise through a MLP, and the discriminative model is also a MLP

In this case, we can train both models using only the BP.

### 3. Related work

- most work focused on models that provided a parametric specification of a probability distribution function. Such as the **deep Boltzmann machine** with intractable likelihood functions
- These difficulties motivated models that do not explicitly represent the likelihood such as **Generative stochastic networks**, This work extends the idea of a generative machine by eliminating the MC.
- Previous work has also taken the approach of using a discriminative criterion to train a generative model. **Noise-contrastive estimation** involves training a generative model by learning the weights that make the model useful for discriminating data from a fixed noise distribution.
- Some previous work has used the concept of having two NNs compete. Such as **predictability minimization**.

### 4. Adversarial nets

To learn the generator’s distribution $ p_g$ over data $x$, we define a prior on input noise variables $p_z(z)$, then represent a mapping to data space as $G(z; θ_g)$. We also define a second multilayer perceptron $D(x; θ_d)$ that outputs a single scalar. $D(x)$ represents the probability that $x$ came from the data rather than $p_g$. $D$ and $G$ play the following two-player minimax game with value function $V (G, D)$:
$$
\min_G \max_D V(G,D)=E_{x\sim p_{data}(x)}[\log D(x)]+E_{z\sim p_z(z)}[\log(1-D(G(z)))]
$$
And here is a  less formal, more pedagogical explanation of the approach. 

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

To avoid overfitting, we between $k$ steps of optimizing $D$ and one step of optimizing $G$. Besides, early in learning, when $G$ is poor, $D$ can reject samples with high confidence, in this case, $\log(1 − D(G(z)))$ saturates. We can train $G$ to maximize $\log D(G(z))$. This function provides much stronger gradients early in learning.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

### 5.  Experiments

The generator nets used a mixture of rectifier linear activations and sigmoid activations, While our theoretical framework permits the use of dropout and other noise at intermediate layers of the generator, we used noise as the input to only the bottommost layer of the generator network.

The discriminator net used maxout activations. Dropout was applied in training the discriminator net. 

### 6.  Conclusions and future work

This framework admits many straightforward extensions:

- A conditional generative model $p(x | c) $ can be obtained by adding $c$ as input to both $G$ and $D$.
- Learned approximate inference can be performed by training an auxiliary network to predict $z$ given $x$.
- Semi-supervised learning: features from the discriminator or inference net could improve performance of classifiers when limited labeled data is available.
- Efficiency improvements: training could be accelerated greatly by devising better methods for coordinating $G$ and $D$ or determining better distributions to sample z from during training.
